where ${\bm \sigma} = \left({\bm \usigma}_x,{\bm \usigma}_y,{\bm \usigma}_z \right)^{\rm T}$ is the vector of Pauli spin matrices.
With this geometric interpretation, we can explain some of the common features of and gain insight into Raman-coupled pseudo-spin-$\nicefrac{1}{2}$ systems. This description is applicable to any optically addressable three-level system, but the application to a spinor BEC is of particular importance because the spatial extent of the atomic cloud captures the spatial variations in the optical parameters.  Furthermore, Raman processes are being explored both experimentally and theoretically as ways of producing features in BECs such as spin textures, synthetic fields, singularities, and even magnetic monopoles. 
